The paper deals with algorithms for networks of processes, which is a topic that falls under distributed computing (cs.DC). The problems studied, such as colouring, degree computation, and MIS, are classic problems in distributed systems and algorithms, which suggests that the paper could also belong to the distributed systems (cs.DS) sub-category. The use of probability and information theory in the algorithms, as well as the mention of a Martingale technique, suggests that the paper could also belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The use of beeps as a communication primitive suggests that the paper could also belong to the networked systems (cs.NI) sub-category. Finally, the study of the relative power of different variants of beeping models suggests that the paper could also belong to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
